## Risks & Mitigations

### Critical Risks

| Risk | Impact | Probability | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Cognitive dependency** — Users atrophy their own memory, becoming unable to function without the system | High | Medium | Design for augmentation, not replacement. Include "memory exercise" features that strengthen biological memory. System should make itself less necessary over time, not more. Clear warnings about over-reliance. |
| **Cognitive Twin manipulation** — The model of the user's cognition is used to manipulate them (even unintentionally through biased predictions) | Critical | Medium | Constitutional constraint: Twin predictions are NEVER used to influence user behavior, only to prepare context. All Twin outputs explicitly labeled as predictions with confidence intervals. User can disable Twin entirely. Regular bias audits. Open-source all Twin logic. |
| **Privacy breach through metadata** — Even with E2E encryption, metadata patterns reveal information (timing of memories, connection patterns, query patterns) | High | Medium | Metadata minimization: server sees only encrypted blobs and CIDs. Padding and dummy operations to obscure access patterns. Optional onion routing for network-level privacy. Local-first architecture means most operations never touch a server. |
| **Legal compulsion** — Governments force users to decrypt memories, or subpoena memory contents | High | Medium | Plausible deniability: support hidden volumes (steganographic). Key deletion: ability to destroy decryption keys irreversibly. Jurisdiction diversity: store encrypted blobs across multiple jurisdictions. Legal guidance documentation. |
| **Cryptographic obsolescence** — Algorithms broken by quantum computing or mathematical advances | High | Low-Medium | Crypto agility: all algorithms are pluggable and migratable. Post-quantum migration path (Kyber/Dilithium ready). Regular algorithm health assessments. Proactive migration before algorithms are broken. |
| **Manipulation through shared memories** — Malicious actors inject false or misleading memories into collaborative spaces | Medium | Medium | Provenance verification: all shared memories have cryptographic origin proofs. Reputation system for memory sources. User confirmation before integrating external memories. Separation between "received memories" and "personal memories" with clear visual distinction. |
| **Traumatic memory management** — System surfaces or preserves memories the user finds harmful | High | Medium | User-controlled content warnings and triggers. "Soft delete" that hides without destroying. Option for "therapeutic mode" — controlled re-exposure with professional guidance. Never surprise the user with emotionally intense memories. |
| **Model drift in Cognitive Twin** — Twin becomes inaccurate over time, leading to bad predictions | Medium | High | Continuous calibration against actual user behavior. Explicit confidence decay for inactive model areas. Regular "twin check-in" prompts where user validates key predictions. Anomaly detection for sudden behavior changes that invalidate the model. |
| **Digital inequality** — System creates a cognitive divide between those who have it and those who don't | Medium | Medium | Open-source core. Free tier with full sovereignty features. Protocol standardization (UMP) enables competition. Avoid lock-in at every level. |
| **Identity theft via memory theft** — Someone who steals your memory essentially steals your cognitive identity | Critical | Low | Multi-factor encryption (password + biometric + hardware key). Key rotation. Tamper detection. Remote wipe capability. Memory isolation: no single key unlocks everything. |

### Architectural Risks

| Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **Memory DNA format bloat** — Self-describing format adds significant overhead per memory | Aggressive optimization: embedded schema is shared across memories of the same type (deduplicated). WASM decoders included only in capsules, not in daily operation. Typical overhead: <500 bytes per memory for self-description. |
| **Dream Engine false positives** — System proposes nonsensical consolidations or connections | Conservative default settings. All proposals require user approval (initially). Confidence thresholds tuned over time with user feedback. "Dream quality" metric tracked per cycle. |
| **MQL complexity** — Query language too complex for most users | Natural language interface that translates to MQL. Pre-built query templates for common operations. Visual query builder. MQL is the power-user layer; most users never see it. |
| **ABE performance** — Attribute-Based Encryption is computationally expensive | ABE used only for shared memories (relatively rare). Personal memories use standard symmetric encryption. ABE operations cached aggressively. Hardware acceleration where available. |
| **Index explosion** — 8+ indices per memory creates storage and update overhead | Indices are lazily built and incrementally maintained. Cold/archive memories have reduced indexing (only semantic + temporal). Index prioritization: only build indices that the user actually queries. |

